---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'About StateWages';
const description = "StateWages exists because every other salary site is either paywalled, self-reported, or both. Here's what we actually use and why it's different.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="about-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">About this site</span>
      <h1>Why I Built This</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <main>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-content">

        <div class="about-body">

          <p class="lead">
            About three years ago I spent an entire weekend trying to figure out if a job offer was worth taking.
            It was in a different state. The salary looked fine on paper, but I had no way to tell if it was fine
            <em>for that market.</em>
          </p>

          <p>
            So I did what most people do: opened Glassdoor, then Payscale, then Indeed, then LinkedIn Salary,
            then back to Glassdoor because maybe I'd missed something. An hour in I had five ranges that didn't
            agree with each other, half behind some signup wall, and none of them could tell me where in the
            distribution I'd actually land. Frustrating in a way that feels disproportionate to how simple the
            question is.
          </p>

          <p>
            Here's the thing nobody really says out loud: most of that data is self-reported. Companies tell
            Glassdoor what they want to tell them. Employees type in whatever number feels right. There's no
            auditing, no consistent methodology, and honestly no good reason to think that 47 responses for
            "marketing manager in Denver" tells you much about the actual market. It might. It might not.
            You can't tell.
          </p>

          <p>
            The federal survey behind this data covers about 1.1 million employers every year. Mandatory participation.
            Consistent methodology going back decades. The full dataset is public and free, covering 800-plus
            occupations across every state. I found it after about two hours of digging through the source site (not
            a great website, for the record). The data was all there, just buried in Excel files with column names
            like A_PCT25 and H_MEDIAN that require cross-referencing a 40-page data dictionary to make sense of.
          </p>

          <p>So I built StateWages. That's the whole story.</p>

          <h2>What the data actually is</h2>

          <p>
            Every number on this site comes from the most current release of the federal Occupational Employment
            and Wage Statistics program. I update the site within a few days whenever a new release drops (usually
            once a year in spring).
          </p>

          <p>
            I download the raw file, run it through a processing script, and generate a page for every
            occupation-state combination that has enough observations to report. When the sample size for a
            particular job in a particular state is too small, the survey suppresses the data and I show "N/A." That's not a
            bug. That's the data telling you there aren't enough observations to give you a number worth trusting,
            and I'd rather show nothing than show something misleading.
          </p>

          <p>
            The tradeoff (and I want to be straight about this) is that the data is a snapshot. It reflects employer
            survey responses from the collection period. Job markets move. If you're in a field that changed
            a lot recently, treat these numbers as a floor, not a ceiling, and check recent job postings too.
          </p>

          <h2>How to actually read a percentile</h2>

          <p>
            Most people see the median and stop. The percentile table is way more useful than that, and I think
            it's worth explaining what those numbers mean in plain terms.
          </p>

          <p>
            The 10th percentile is roughly what someone just starting out earns, or what the job pays in a low-cost
            area with a small employer. The 90th percentile is a senior person at a large employer in a high-cost city.
            The median (50th percentile) is the middle of the market: half earn more, half earn less. When you're
            looking at a job offer and you want to know if it's good, the relevant question isn't whether it's above
            the median. It's where it falls relative to what someone with your experience level typically earns. That's
            usually somewhere in the 25th to 75th range, and the specific number shifts a lot by location.
          </p>

          <p>
            A registered nurse in California earns a median of about $125,000. In Mississippi it's around $63,000.
            Same license. Same job title. Same federal occupation code. The state is doing almost all the work there,
            and that's a real thing worth knowing before you take a job or move.
          </p>

          <h2>What this site isn't</h2>

          <p>
            Not a job board. Not trying to sell you a resume service or connect you with recruiters (though I'd be
            lying if I said I never thought about adding affiliate links to job boards). There are no accounts, no
            surveys, no premium tiers. The data is public and the site is free because there's really no reason
            it shouldn't be.
          </p>

          <p>
            The site runs display ads. That's how it stays free and how I cover the time I put into it. I'd rather
            be upfront about that than pretend it's purely altruistic.
          </p>

          <div class="about-note">
            <strong>If a number looks wrong:</strong> the most likely explanation is data suppression or a rounding
            difference in how the source reports certain fields. The raw data lives at
            <a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bls.gov/oes</a> (that's the only
            place I'll name the survey by its official acronym). If you find a genuine error in how I've processed the data, I want to know about it.
          </div>

        </div>

        <aside class="about-sidebar">
          <div class="info-block">
            <h3>Site facts</h3>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">📊</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Data source</div><div class="info-value">Current release</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">🗂️</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Occupations covered</div><div class="info-value">800+</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">🗺️</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">States covered</div><div class="info-value">All 50 + DC</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">📅</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Updated</div><div class="info-value">Annually each May</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="info-row">
              <div class="info-icon">💰</div>
              <div><div class="info-label">Cost to use</div><div class="info-value">Free</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="info-block">
            <h3>Useful links</h3>
            <ul class="related-links">
              <li><a href="https://www.bls.gov/oes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OEWS at bls.gov</a></li>
              <li><a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Occupational Outlook Handbook</a></li>
              <li><a href="/privacy-policy/">Privacy Policy</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-hero {
    background: var(--bg-inset);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding: 3rem 0 2.5rem;
  }

  .about-content {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 240px;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    padding: 2.5rem 0 5rem;
  }

  .about-body { max-width: 640px; }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .about-body p { line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.1rem; }

  .about-body h2 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    margin-top: 2.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .about-body ul { margin-bottom: 1.1rem; }
  .about-body li { line-height: 1.65; margin-bottom: 0.45rem; }

  .about-note {
    background: var(--primary-light);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--primary);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--primary-dark);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .about-sidebar { position: sticky; top: calc(58px + 1rem); }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .about-content { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .about-sidebar { position: static; }
  }
</style>
